Thus , in the forty ninth year of his age , falling at the same time of his career as Strafford had fallen in his , perished Charles the First . 
Indeed , I am afraid that he was but a bad judge of martyrs for he had called that infamous Duke of Buckingham 'the Martyr of his Sovereign . 
, they then appointed a Council of State to govern the country . 
It consisted of forty one members , of whom five were peers . 
The House of Commons also re admitted members who had opposed the King's death , and made up its numbers to about a hundred and fifty . 
But , it still had an army of more than forty thousand men to deal with , and a very hard task it was to manage them . 
Before the King's execution , the army had appointed some of its officers to remonstrate between them and the Parliament and now the common soldiers began to take that office upon themselves . 
The regiments under orders for Ireland mutinied one troop of horse in the city of London seized their own flag , and refused to obey orders . 
The soldiers soon found , as all men did , that Oliver was not a man to be trifled with . 
And there was an end of the mutiny . 
He was soon taken prisoner and carried to Edinburgh . 
There he was received with every possible insult , and carried to prison in a cart , his officers going two and two before him . 
He went to the scaffold in a bright and brilliant dress , and made a bold end at thirty eight years of age . 
The breath was scarcely out of his body when Charles abandoned his memory , and denied that he had ever given him orders to rise in his behalf . 
There were numbers of friars and priests among them , and Oliver gruffly wrote home in his despatch that these were 'knocked on the head' like the rest . 
, and he imitated the example of his father in law with such good will that he brought the country to subjection , and laid it at the feet of the Parliament . 
These were sweeping measures but , if Oliver Cromwell had had his own way fully , and had stayed in Ireland , he would have done more yet . 
